        {
            "id": "m1-p2",
            "title": "Terminal Points on the Unit Circle",
            "blocks": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The circumference of the unit circle is C = 2\u03c0(1) = 2\u03c0. Starting at (1, 0), the distance traveled along the circle matches an angle measure in radians."
                },
                {
                    "type": "katex",
                    "expression": "C = 2\\pi(1) = 2\\pi",
                    "displayMode": true
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If a point moves counterclockwise from (1, 0): half a circle is a distance of \u03c0, a quarter circle is \u03c0/2, and three quarters is 3\u03c0/2. These distances determine terminal points on the unit circle."
                },
                {
                    "type": "katex",
                    "expression": "t=\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\Rightarrow P(0,1),\\quad t=\\pi\\Rightarrow P(-1,0),\\quad t=\\frac{3\\pi}{2}\\Rightarrow P(0,-1),\\quad t=2\\pi\\Rightarrow P(1,0)",
                    "displayMode": true
                },
                {
                    "type": "image",
                    "src": "/lessons/precalc/imgs/Screenshot 2026-02-11 101715.png",
                    "alt": "Unit circle reference diagram",
                    "caption": "",
                    "maxWidth": 700
                },
                {
                    "type": "desmos",
                    "title": "Visualize terminal points for \u03c0/2, \u03c0, 3\u03c0/2, and 2\u03c0",
                    "expressions": [
                        "x^2+y^2=1",
                        {
                            "latex": "A=(1,0)",
                            "label": "P(1,0)",
                            "showLabel": true
                        },
                        {
                            "latex": "B=(0,1)",
                            "label": "P(0,1)",
                            "showLabel": true
                        },
                        {
                            "latex": "C=(-1,0)",
                            "label": "P(-1,0)",
                            "showLabel": true
                        },
                        {
                            "latex": "D=(0,-1)",
                            "label": "P(0,-1)",
                            "showLabel": true
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Example: Find the terminal point on the unit circle determined by each real number t."
                },
                {
                    "type": "question",
                    "id": "m1q2",
                    "prompt": "(a) t = 3\u03c0. What is the terminal point?",
                    "acceptableAnswers": [
                        "(-1,0)",
                        "(-1, 0)",
                        "P(-1,0)",
                        "p(-1,0)"
                    ],
                    "explanation": "A full turn is 2\u03c0, so 3\u03c0 is equivalent to \u03c0."
                },
                {
                    "type": "question",
                    "id": "m1q3",
                    "prompt": "(b) t = -\u03c0. What is the terminal point?",
                    "acceptableAnswers": [
                        "(-1,0)",
                        "(-1, 0)",
                        "P(-1,0)",
                        "p(-1,0)"
                    ],
                    "explanation": "Negative angles move clockwise. -\u03c0 lands at the same point as \u03c0."
                },
                {
                    "type": "question",
                    "id": "m1q4",
                    "prompt": "(c) t = -\u03c0/2. What is the terminal point?",
                    "acceptableAnswers": [
                        "(0,-1)",
                        "(0, -1)",
                        "P(0,-1)",
                        "p(0,-1)"
                    ],
                    "explanation": "-\u03c0/2 is a quarter-turn clockwise from (1,0)."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}